# Status Colors

For account, purchase, payment, and license states:

| State             |       Hex | Example            |
| ----------------- | --------: | ------------------ |
| Paid / Active     | `#00E676` | Purchase active    |
| Pending / Warning | `#FFB020` | Payment pending    |
| Failed / Error    | `#FF4D5E` | Payment failed     |
| Info              | `#00CFFF` | Download available |

```css
--success: #00E676;
--warning: #FFB020;
--error: #FF4D5E;
--info: #00CFFF;
```

Use these only for status, not for normal decoration.

---

# Best Visual Ratio

Use the colors like this:

| Color Type                        |   Usage |
| --------------------------------- | ------: |
| Dark navy backgrounds             | **70%** |
| White / soft white text           | **20%** |
| Cyan accents                      |  **8%** |
| Green / amber / red status colors |  **2%** |

This is important. If cyan is used everywhere, it loses power. Cyan should guide the user’s eye to important actions.

---

# Recommended Final Look

Your Imperium Store should follow this style:

```text
Dark navy base
+ clean white typography
+ cyan CTA buttons
+ subtle cyan borders
+ soft glow only on important actions
+ green/amber/red only for purchase/account status
```

This will make the site feel more like a **serious trading software store** instead of a generic ecommerce page.



Yes, **amber can be used**, but not as a main brand color.

For Imperium Store, cyan should remain the **primary brand accent**. Amber should be a **secondary attention color** used only where you want urgency, premium highlights, or trading-related emphasis.

---

# Best Uses for Amber

## 1. Limited-Time / Important Badges

Amber works very well for offer-style labels:

```text
LIMITED ACCESS
NEW
POPULAR
BEST VALUE
EARLY USER PRICE
```

Recommended amber:

```css
--amber: #FFB020;
--amber-soft: rgba(255, 176, 32, 0.14);
--amber-border: rgba(255, 176, 32, 0.38);
```

Example:

```css
.badge-amber {
  color: #FFB020;
  background: rgba(255, 176, 32, 0.12);
  border: 1px solid rgba(255, 176, 32, 0.35);
}
```

---

## 2. Price Highlights

Amber can be used near the price, but not for the entire price everywhere.

Good usage:

```text
₹6,999
One-time access
```

Use amber for the small supporting label:

```css
.price-note {
  color: #FFB020;
}
```

Avoid making all prices amber. White or cyan is cleaner for the main price.

---

## 3. Warning / Pending States

Amber is perfect for account and payment states:

| State                 |     Color |
| --------------------- | --------: |
| Payment pending       | `#FFB020` |
| License expiring soon | `#FFB020` |
| Update available      | `#FFB020` |
| Action required       | `#FFB020` |

Example:

```css
.status-warning {
  color: #FFB020;
  background: rgba(255, 176, 32, 0.12);
  border: 1px solid rgba(255, 176, 32, 0.35);
}
```

---

## 4. Premium Feature Markers

Amber can signal “premium” without looking cheap.

Use it for:

```text
PRO
PREMIUM
ADVANCED
LIFETIME
```

Example:

```css
.premium-label {
  color: #FFB020;
  text-shadow: 0 0 14px rgba(255, 176, 32, 0.22);
}
```

---

# Where Not to Use Amber

Avoid amber for:

* Main background
* Navbar
* Normal buttons
* Main product card border
* Normal links
* Large text blocks
* Too many icons

Too much amber will fight with cyan and make the site look less premium.

---

# Best Rule

Use the colors like this:

| Color         | Purpose                                  |
| ------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| **Dark navy** | Base and background                      |
| **White**     | Main text                                |
| **Cyan**      | Brand, buttons, active states            |
| **Amber**     | Warnings, premium labels, limited offers |
| **Green**     | Success / paid                           |
| **Red**       | Error / failed                           |

---

# Final Recommendation

Add amber to your palette, but use it as an **attention color**, not a brand color.

```css
:root {
  --warning-amber: #FFB020;
  --warning-amber-soft: rgba(255, 176, 32, 0.12);
  --warning-amber-border: rgba(255, 176, 32, 0.35);
}
```

For Imperium Store, amber is best for:

```text
POPULAR
BEST VALUE
UPDATE AVAILABLE
LICENSE EXPIRING
PAYMENT PENDING
PREMIUM FEATURE
```

Cyan should still own the main identity. Amber should appear only when something needs special attention.

Yes, **gold can work better than amber** for Imperium Store — but only if you want a more **premium / luxury / high-value software** feel.

For your brand:

```text
Dark navy + cyan = technology / trading / execution
Dark navy + gold = premium / wealth / authority
Dark navy + cyan + gold = premium fintech / trading software
```

But gold should be used **even more carefully** than amber.

---

# Gold vs Amber

| Color                   | Feeling                   | Best Use                                     |
| ----------------------- | ------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| **Amber** `#FFB020`     | Warning, attention, alert | Pending, notice, update, caution             |
| **Gold** `#D4AF37`      | Premium, luxury, value    | Pro badge, lifetime access, featured product |
| **Soft Gold** `#F5D76E` | Highlight, shine          | Small decorative highlights                  |
| **Dark Gold** `#9F7A18` | Serious premium           | Borders, subtle icons                        |

