# Best Places to Use Gold

## 1. Premium Product Badge

Use gold for labels like:

```text
PRO
PREMIUM
BEST VALUE
LIFETIME ACCESS
FEATURED
```

Example:

```css
.badge-gold {
  color: #F5D76E;
  background: rgba(212, 175, 55, 0.12);
  border: 1px solid rgba(212, 175, 55, 0.35);
  box-shadow: 0 0 18px rgba(212, 175, 55, 0.18);
}
```

---

## 2. Featured Product Card

For your main product, you can use a **very subtle gold border**:

```css
.featured-card {
  border: 1px solid rgba(212, 175, 55, 0.32);
  box-shadow:
    0 0 22px rgba(212, 175, 55, 0.12),
    0 18px 40px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.35);
}
```

Do not make the whole card gold. Only use gold on the edge, badge, or small highlight.

---

## 3. Price Accent

Gold is good for **small price-support text**, not necessarily the main price.

Good:

```text
₹6,999
Lifetime Access
```

Use gold for **Lifetime Access**:

```css
.price-note {
  color: #D4AF37;
}
```

For the main price, I still prefer:

```css
.price {
  color: #FFFFFF;
}
```

or:

```css
.price {
  color: #00CFFF;
}
```

---

# Where Not to Use Gold

Avoid gold for:

* Main buttons
* Navbar links
* Normal body text
* Large backgrounds
* Every product card border
* Normal icons
* Error / warning messages

Gold everywhere will make the site look heavy. Use it as a **premium signal**.

---

# Final Recommendation for Imperium Store

Use this hierarchy:

| Role           |           Color |
| -------------- | --------------: |
| Brand accent   |  Cyan `#00CFFF` |
| Premium accent |  Gold `#D4AF37` |
| Warning color  | Amber `#FFB020` |
| Success color  | Green `#00E676` |
| Error color    |   Red `#FF4D5E` |

Best balance:

```text
70% dark navy
18% white / gray text
8% cyan
3% gold
1% status colors
```

So yes — **use gold**, but use it only for **premium, featured, lifetime, pro, and high-value elements**.

For Imperium Store, I would use:

```text
Cyan = action
Gold = premium value
Amber = warning
```

That separation will make the design cleaner and more professional.
